  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical buzzword—it's something I've seen play out in my own shop. Growing up with parents who both had higher education, I never really thought about how my gender or background might affect my ability to succeed in fields like engineering or physics. But when I started working with kids who were struggling to get into technical programs, I noticed something: they'd start doubting themselves the moment they walked into a classroom or workshop, thinking, 'Am I good enough?' That's stereotype threat in action. It's the invisible weight that comes from believing you don't belong in a space where you're expected to excel. For me, as a mechanic who's spent decades fixing cars and machines, I know that confidence comes from hands-on experience and trust in your skills. But for students who don't see themselves reflected in STEM fields, the fear of being judged or failing can be paralyzing. Should we address it? Absolutely. It's not about changing the system overnight, but about creating environments where everyone feels safe to try, to ask questions, and to make mistakes. I've seen it work in my own shop—when I let my apprentices know they're learning at their own pace and that mistakes are part of the process, they start to believe in themselves. The key is to make sure that everyone, regardless of their background, feels like they belong. It's not about fixing the stereotype itself but about building bridges where people can thrive without the fear of being labeled. In my experience, that starts with listening, with patience, and with showing up for the people who need it most.",
